</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <div class="container">
            <h1><span class="gradient-text">ud83dudcac Comment Vibes ud83dudcac</span></h1>
            <p class="subtitle">Spill the tea in your code!</p>
        </div>
    </header>

    <main class="container">
        <div class="doc-grid">
            <aside class="sidebar">
                <nav>
                    <ul>
                        <li><a href="installation.html">Getting Started</a></li>
                        <li><a href="basic-types.html">Basic Types</a></li>
                        <li><a href="#" class="active">Comment Vibes</a></li>
                        <li><a href="variables.html">Variables</a></li>
                        <li><a href="functions.html">Functions</a></li>
                    </ul>
                </nav>
            </aside>

            <article class="content">
                <section class="intro">
                    <div class="tag-container">
                        <span class="tag">Core Syntax</span>
                        <span class="tag">Documentation</span>
                        <span class="tag">Spill The Tea</span>
                    </div>
                    <p class="lead">Comments in CURSED are where you can spill the tea about your code. They're ignored by the compiler but help humans understand your vibe.</p>
                </section>

                <section>
                    <h2>u2728 Comment Types u2728</h2>
                    <p>CURSED has two ways to drop comments in your code:</p>
                    
                    <div class="feature-grid">
                        <div class="feature-card">
                            <h3>Line Comments <span class="tag">fr fr</span></h3>
                            <p>Start with <code>fr fr</code> and continue until the end of the line. Perfect for quick notes.</p>
                            <div class="code-block">
                                <div class="code-title">line_comment.csd</div>
                                <pre><code>sus x = 10;  fr fr This is a variable
sus y = 20;  fr fr This is another one</code></pre>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        
                        <div class="feature-card">
                            <h3>Block Comments <span class="tag">no cap ... on god</span></h3>
                            <p>Start with <code>no cap</code> and end with <code>on god</code>. Great for multi-line tea spilling.</p>
                            <div class="code-block">
                                <div class="code-title">block_comment.csd</div>
                                <pre><code>no cap
This function calculates the total vibe check
for an entire array of mood values.
It's giving complexity O(n).
on god
slay calculateVibeTotal(moods []normie) normie {
    // function code here
}</code></pre>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="tips">
                    <h2>Comment Etiquette ud83dudc85</h2>
                    <div class="tips-grid">
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">ud83dudcad</div>
                            <h3>Explain Why, Not What</h3>
                            <p>Comments should explain WHY code exists, not WHAT it does (the code should be self-explanatory).</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">ud83dudca1</div>
                            <h3>Document Gotchas</h3>
                            <p>Use comments to highlight edge cases, potential bugs, or surprising behaviors.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">ud83dudcdd</div>
                            <h3>Function Comments</h3>
                            <p>Document functions with a block comment before the declaration, explaining purpose, parameters, and return values.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="tip-card">
                            <div class="tip-icon">ud83eudde9</div>
                            <h3>Keep It Fresh</h3>
                            <p>Update comments when you change code. Stale comments are worse than no comments!</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section>
                    <h2>ud83dudccd Documentation Comments</h2>
                    <p>For proper documentation, use block comments with a specific format:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">doc_comment.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>no cap
# CalcVibeScore

Calculates a numerical score for the overall vibe of an input string.

## Parameters
- text: The input string to analyze
- sensitivity: How sensitive the algorithm should be (1-10)

## Returns
- normie: A score from 0-100 representing the vibe quality
- error: Any error encountered during analysis

## Example
```
sus score, err = CalcVibeScore("This party is lit", 5);
```
on god
slay CalcVibeScore(text tea, sensitivity normie) (normie, error) {
    // Implementation here
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="example-section">
                    <h2>ud83dudcda Real-World Examples</h2>
                    <p>Here are some examples of effective commenting in CURSED code:</p>
                    
                    <div class="code-block">
                        <div class="code-title">good_comments.csd</div>
                        <pre><code>fr fr Configuration constants for the app
facts MAX_USERS normie = 1000;
facts TIMEOUT_MS normie = 30000;
facts DEFAULT_THEME tea = "neon";

no cap
UserManager handles all user-related operations including:
- Authentication
- Profile management
- Permission checking
- Session handling

It maintains an internal cache of active users for performance.
on god
be_like UserManager squad {
    activeUsers tea[tea]User;
    sessionTimes tea[tea]normie;
    maxCacheSize normie;
    
    fr fr Boolean flag to enable debug logging
    debugMode lit;
}

slay processData(input []byte) []byte {
    sus result []byte = make([]byte, len(input));
    
    bestie (sus i = 0; i < len(input); i++) {
        fr fr Skip null bytes as they cause issues with our parser
        lowkey input[i] == 0 {
            simp;  fr fr continue to next iteration
        }
        
        fr fr Apply XOR transformation with key byte 0x42
        result[i] = input[i] ^ 0x42;
    }
    
    yolo result;
}</code></pre>
                    </div>
                </section>

                <section class="anti-patterns">
                    <h2>u26d4 Comment Anti-Patterns</h2>
                    <p>Avoid these comment vibes - they're not giving what they should:</p>
                    
                    <div class="anti-pattern-card">
                        <h3>Captain Obvious Comments</h3>
                        <div class="code-block">
                            <div class="code-title">bad_comments.csd</div>
                            <pre><code>fr fr Initialize x to 5
sus x = 5;

fr fr Loop from 0 to 9
bestie (sus i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    fr fr Print i
    console.print(i);
}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    
                    <div class="anti-pattern-card">
                        <h3>Comment Novels</h3>
                        <div class="code-block">
                            <div class="code-title">too_much.csd</div>
                            <pre><code>no cap
This function calculates the factorial of a number. Factorial is a mathematical
operation that multiplies a number by all positive integers less than it.
For example, factorial of 5 (written as 5!) is 5 × 4 × 3 × 2 × 1 = 120.
Factorials are used in many areas of mathematics, particularly
combinatorics and probability theory. The factorial operation grows very
quickly - 10! is already over 3 million, and 20! is over 2.4 quintillion.
This implementation uses a simple iterative approach rather than recursion
to avoid stack overflow issues. We could use recursion but that would be less
efficient for large numbers due to the call stack overhead.
on god
slay factorial(n normie) normie {
    sus result = 1;
    for (sus i = 2; i <= n; i++) {
        result *= i;
    }
    yolo result;
}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </section>

